definition.value: Dianion of dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-D-galactose arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of N-phosphotaurocyamine arising from deprotonation of phosphoramidate and sulfonate OH groups and protonation of the guanidino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of 3-dehydro-2-deoxy-D-gluconic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A benzothiadiazine consisting of a 3,4-dihydro-HH-1,2,4-benzothiadiazine bicyclic system dioxygenated on sulfur and carrying trifluoromethyl and aminosulfonyl groups at positions 6 and 7 respectively. A diuretic with actions and uses similar to those of hydrochlorothiazide.
A guanidinium ion that is the conjugate acid of methylguanidine; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of 4-amino-2-methyl-5-diphosphooxymethylpyrimidine arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of vitexin 2''-O-beta-D-glucoside arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-selenocysteine having a anionic carboxy group and a cationic amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of L-methionine having a anionic carboxy group and a cationic amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Octaanion of preuroporphyrinogen arising from global deprotonation of the eight carboxy groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of L-fuculose 1-phosphate arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of UDP-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Dication of 1,4-diguanidinobutane arising from deprotonation of both guanidino groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of (R)-4-dehydropantoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-O-(4-deoxy-alpha-L-threo-hex-4-enopyranosyluronic acid)-D-galactosamine; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate acid of tropinone; major species at pH 7.3.
A  dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the conjugate base of  prephenic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of hypotaurine arising from migration of a proton from the sulfonate group to the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate acid of 4-guanidinobutanal; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion that is the conjugate base of protochlorophyllide, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Zwitterionic form of S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine arising from migration of a proton from the carboxy group to the alpha-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of N-acetyl-beta-alanine; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of atropine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Dicarboxylate anion of  5-(3-carboxy-3-oxopropenyl)-4,6-dihydroxypyridine-2-carboxylic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of dethiobiotin; major species at pH 7.3.
Diphthamide residue protonated on the alpha-nitrogen.
Dianion of ADP-D-glycero-D-manno-heptose; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of 5D-(5/6)-2,6-dihydroxy-5-(hydroxymethyl)cyclohex-2-en-1-one arising from selective deprotonation of the 2-hydroxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A pyrimidine nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of UMP.
Conjugate acid of 3-methylthiopropylamine; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of a nucleoside 5'-phosphate.
An organic sulfamate oxoanion resulting from the removal of the proton from the sulfamic acid group of N-sulfo-D-glucosamine.
Zwitterionic form of 6-aminopenicillanic acid arising from migration of a proton from the carboxy group to the 6-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Tetraanion of D-ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate arising from deprotonation of all four phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate acid of codeine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
Tricarboxylate anion of (2Z)-but-2-ene-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of (S)-reticuline, arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 2-O-(beta-D-glucosyl)-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
The ammonium betaine of a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of CDP-ethanolamine arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of N-acetyl-D-tryptophan; major species at pH 7.3.

An organosulfate oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from both the carboxy group and the sulfate group of 2-acetamido-2-deoxy-3-O-(4-deoxy-alpha-L-threo-hex-4-enopyranosyluronic acid)-6-O-sulfo-D-galactopyranose arising from deprotonation of carboxy and sulfate groups; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of 4-methylene-L-glutamine having an anionic carboxy group and a cationic amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of a 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol; major species at pH 7.3.
Conjugate base of erythro-5-phosphonooxy-L-lysine in which the carboxy and phospho groups are anionic and both primary amino groups are cationic; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 4-carboxymethyl-3-methylbut-2-en-1,4-olide; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium betaine that is the conjugate base of 3-dehydrocarnitinium; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of 2'-deoxy-5-methyl-5'-cytidylic acid arising from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An  ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of tryptamine arising from protonation of the primary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of 4-carboxymethyl-4-methylbut-2-en-1,4-olide; major species at pH 7.3.
